It gives Google more understanding about your content when you use keywords in your content, such as the title and header tags. Your content is more likely to be matched to the appropriate search queries when the algorithm can understand it.

2. Relevancy

When someone says that contents must be relevant, what they really mean is that it must be relevant to the search query. Do your articles, in other words, respond to the queries that initially prompted a user to search on Google?

The words in your search query, the relevancy and usability of the sites, the authority of the sources, and your location and settings are just a few of the numerous elements and signals that search algorithms use to provide you the most helpful information.
Additionally, Google's Algorithm may regard queries as concepts rather than just terms because it is able to comprehend the motivation behind each one.

Because of this, Google will know right away if you are the most relevant and authoritative result for a given search query if you are listed higher on the search result pages. These Google results pages reply to certain keyword and phrase-based search queries.

2. Load these into Python's rdflib

4. build nxontology graph and tabular exports

1) Although the electricity required to handle a single query may be miniscule, ChatGPT reportedly has so many users that the total energy consumption is noticeable.

9/12

3) We don't know neither if BLOOM batched queries or if ChatGPT does. If ChatGPT does and BLOOM didn't, ChatGPT is probably significantly more energy efficient although I don't know the relationship between batch size and energy consumption.

8/12 

1) One BLOOM instance ran on 16 A100 GPUs and to my knowledge we don't know if that's the case for ChatGPT

2) ChatGPT's pre-processing of queries could be more efficient than BLOOM's

3/12 
Number of ChatGPT visits in January: 590m (https://t.co/xfyRm4icF5)

Assuming the bare minimum, let's say each visit resulted in 1 query.

Total ChatGPT queries in January = 590m (based on estimates and assumptions)

2/12 BLOOM is a language model similar in size to ChatGPT's underlying language model, GPT-3. 

BLOOM once consumed 914 KWh during a period where it handled 230,768 queries.

So BLOOM's electricity consumption per query = 0,00396 KWh (based on facts)

Use

GROUP BY ROLLUP ( ... )

This adds subtotals working right to left through the columns

So ROLLUP ( dept_id, job_id ) =>

( dept_id, job_id )
( dept_id )
grand total
